<DOCNO> AP900719-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here are selected quotations from the books 
and speeches of dr karl menninger the psychiatrist who died 
wednesday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
gone forever is the notion that the mentally ill person is an 
exception it is now accepted that most people have some degree of 
mental illness at some time and many of them have a degree of 
mental illness most of the time this should not surprise anyone 
for do not most of us have some physical illness some of the time 
and some of us much of the time from his book the vital 
balance 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
we all look for miracles in the relief of our distress but 
psychotherapy lays no claim to miracle performings all it can do 
is to present certain aspects of the truth and by this as we are 
often reminded some are set free loneliness may disappear as you 
know yourself better and become aware of conflicts within that 
prevent you from getting close to others from the book man 
against himself 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sigmund freuds great courage led him to look honestly at 
the evil in mans nature freud persisted in his researches to the 
bottom of the jar and there he found hope he discerned that love 
is stronger than hate that hence for all its core of malignancy 
the nature of man can be transformed through the nurture and 
dispersion of love in this way the destructiveness can be 
transcended from the book the vital balance 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the vast majority of ailing minds never see psychiatrists and 
never will and many of them never should but the principles of 
psychiatry should be applied all the same sometimes they can be 
selfadministered sometimes a friend will turn the trick the 
family doctor or clergyman often does it and sometimes a book 
will do it from the book the human mind 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
most people never see the awfulness of war they only read 
about it or hear about it from reporters or survivors war 
continues to be a deputized human activity some citizens are sent 
out to do what the total citizenry couldnt and wouldnt do the 
rest of us stand or sit a long way off and watch or listen 
occasionally from the book whatever became of sin 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
to many of us the war in vietnam seems a prime example of 
selfdestructiveness one more likely to spread communism and other 
evils than to control them youths are being sacrificed money 
materials the country our own national image and in many places 
our goodwill are being destroyed in a continuing pointless and 
as it seems to many of us futile military bonfire testimony 
before the us senate foreign relations committee june 19 1969 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900719-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the earthquake that struck the main 
philippines island of luzon caught president corazon aquinos 
government illprepared for disaster and dramatized her 
administrations organizational shortcomings 
three days after the quake which measured 77 on the richter 
scale the government has no comprehensive picture of the extent of 
damage and casualties 
relief operations appear centered in areas such as baguio where 
media focused its attention 
the immediate task is the rescue and feeding of survivors 
said the newspaper malaya three days after the earthquake the 
abject failure of the government on this score is appalling 
even in baguio a lack of coordination among government agencies 
was clear 
the office of civil defense counted 82 people dead in baguio 
110 miles to the north chief of staff gen renato de villa said 91 
were killed and the red cross estimated 118 dead 
poor communications forced local officials to use private radio 
and television stations to alert manila of the devastation and 
appeal for help 
today rep simeon garcia told radio station dzmm that about 100 
motorists stranded by the quake were at his home in nueva ecija 
province waiting for help promised by the army days ago but as yet 
unreceived 
clearly if we hope to reduce the number of deaths and the 
extent of the damage wrought by natural calamities we as a nation 
must give priority to disaster monitoring prediction and 
preparedness the philippine daily inquirer said today 
problems of communication and coordination emerged within 
moments of the mondays quake when mrs aquino dispatched 
officials to survey the damage in manila and ordered the military 
to ferry stranded commuters 
few military trucks appeared on the streets and tens of 
thousands of commuters wound up walking home 
that typified the governments reaction to the crisis good 
intentions but neither the resources nor the organization to 
implement them 
the temblor struck about a half hour before government offices 
normally close for the day most state employees simply went home 
early fearing another quake 
soon afterward the presidential press office announced that the 
government was studying the extent of damage 
it was only after commercial radio stations broadcast damage 
reports from their provincial affiliates that the government began 
to respond 
first reports focused on cabanatuan city 60 miles north of 
manila where a sixstory school collapsed trapping hundreds of 
students and teachers 
on tuesday mrs aquino flew to the city for her first view of 
the relief operations reporters who traveled with her said she was 
angry over what she saw 
whos in charge aides quoted her as asking local officials 
the rescue operation is so slow why 
only after returning from cabanatuan did she declare a state 
of calamity in affected provinces on wednesday she hurredly 
added la union province to the list after radio and television 
stations broadcast first reports of massive destruction there 
the government maintains a system of regional disaster 
coordinating councils which are supposed to marshal the nations 
resources to cope with calamities 
but the regional committees lack money equipment 
communications and trained rescue personnel cabanatuan mayor 
honorato perez used commercial radio stations to beg manila for 
cranes jackhammers and trained rescuers 
the government sent troops to cabanatuan but they were no 
better trained in rescue operations than the civilian volunteers 
in baguio where the temblor damaged the airport runway and cut 
land routes into the city stocks of emergency supplies and 
equipment were insufficient to mount an effective relief operation 
even if local authorities were better equipped the highly 
centralized government structure tends to inhibit grassroots 
initiatives the simplest request often turns into a bureaucratic 
nightmare 
for example as the philippines appealed to the world for help 
the office of the president produced implementing guidelines 
for receiving foreign donations 
interested overseas donors or their local representatives are 
to submit written offers to the presidential management staff once 
notified of the governments acceptance the donors are to submit a 
bill of lading or airway bill for clearance by the presidential 
management staff which in turn transmits all necessary documents 
to the bureau of customs the bureau of customs initiates the 
processing of import documents and releases the donation to the 
office of the president finally the office of the president turns 
over the donations to the designated recipient agency or 
organization 
such disorderly responses are sadly routine nearly every time 
disaster strikes 
during typhoons comprehensive reports of damage and casualties 
often take days or even weeks to reach manila delaying the 
shipment of food medicine and supplies to the victims 
the lack of coordination seems all the more surprising because 
an average of 20 typhoons strike the philippines annually some 
routinely kill hundreds 
from the moment the quake struck until this very 
moment we have had to play it by ear and improvise said the 
manila times many of the hundreds of people killed in this 
latest disaster could have been spared if only we had all taken to 
heart the deadly serious business of disaster preparedness 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

