<DOCNO> AP900719-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the remains of former bulgarian leader 
georgi dimitrov revered as national hero during communist rule 
have been removed from a downtown mausoleum and cremated the state 
news agency bta reported 
it said wednesday that the cremation took place in the presence 
of relatives suggesting the procedure took place overnight to 
avoid publicity 
despite longtime official veneration dimitrov has become 
increasingly unpopular particularly in sofia where the 
noncommunist opposition union of democratic forces emerged as 
clear winner in last months multiparty elections 
the mausoleum that had held dimitrovs remains has been guarded 
around the clock by two soldiers in traditional balkanstyle dress 
uniform equipped with bayonettopped rifles 
a leading figure in the international communist movement 
dimitrov was acquitted in a trial in late 1933 in which he was 
charged with complicity in the fire that destroyed the german 
reichstag parliament building 
historians say the arson was a nazi provocation 
in 1946 dimitrov became leader of the bulgarian communist party 
and also headed the government until his death in 1949 
under dimitrov noncommunist opposition parties were either 
disbanded or merged in a communistdominated mass organization 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900719-0007 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
moscows decision to drop its objection to 
nato membership for a reunited germany likely will put eastwest 
arms control negotiations back on track administration officials 
and private arms control experts say 
defense secretary dick cheney told reporters wednesday that 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachevs concession on german 
participation in the north atlantic treaty organization removed 
the last roadblock to clinching two landmark arms control 
agreements 
cheney referred to 23nation negotiations to sharply reduce the 
number of conventional arms tanks troops and aircraft in 
europe and to ussoviet talks on slashing strategic or 
longrange nuclear missiles by onethird 
the conventional arms negotiations have been bogged down for 
months by several key disputes including nato resistance to a 
soviet demand that the west german government of chancellor helmut 
kohl accept a numerical limit on its armed forces 
kohl had said his country must not be singled out for such 
limits but at his summit with gorbachev on monday kohl agreed 
that a united germany would have no more than 370000 troops in its 
army 45 percent fewer than the present combined strength of the 
east and west germanys armed forces 
in return gorbachev withdrew his objections to permitting a 
united germany in nato whose leaders pledged at a meeting in 
london on july 6 to relax their military readiness and reduce their 
reliance on nuclear arms 
settlement of the german troop strength question is likely to 
give new life to the eastwest conventional arms negotiations under 
way in vienna arms control analysts said wednesday 
it definitely helps said david shorr associate director of 
the british american security information council a research group 
based in washington and london 
shorr said the kohlgorbachev deal made it increasingly likely 
that the vienna negotiators will meet their unofficial deadline of 
completing a treaty in time for a 35nation summit to be held in 
paris on nov 19 to ratify a new political relationship among the 
united states the soviet union canada and all of europe 
some obstacles to a conventional forces agreement are yet to be 
worked out they include 
whether a limit should be placed on individual nations shares 
of the total number of troops allowed in europe 
which kinds of aircraft should be counted in the military 
equipment limits 
under what circumstances a country would be allowed to convert 
military equipment to civilian use 
how often each country would have to permit inspections of 
conventional arms on its soil 
the kohlgorbachev agreement appeared to have little direct 
application to the ussoviet strategic arms reduction talks to 
reduce longrange nuclear missile arsenals although cheney 
mentioned start in saying arms agreements were now more likely 
cheney did not elaborate on this point but analysts said they 
believed resolution of the last remaining major political obstacle 
to german reunification would make it easier for washington and 
moscow to resolve their start disagreements 
the national security bureaucracies in both countries have 
been preoccupied with these questions of german reunification 
said dunbar lockwood who studies start issues for the private arms 
control association now they can start thinking about arms 
control again 
three major issues remain unresolved in the start talks which 
gorbachev and president bush have said they hope to complete by the 
end of this year the stickiest issue is how far the soviets will 
be allowed to go in modernizing their ss18 intercontinental 
ballistic missiles which form the backbone of the soviet nuclear 
arsenal 
the two other unresolved matters are limits on the soviet 
backfire bomber and soviet efforts to restrict us sales of 
strategic nuclear systems to britain 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

