<DOCNO> AP900719-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
convicted spy jonathan pollard served his wife 
with divorce papers wednesday at the hospital where she is being 
treated for a gastrointestinal disorder mrs pollards attorney 
said 
in seeking the divorce jonathan pollard cited irreconcilable 
differences and the fact that he has not lived with his wife 
since his arrest in november 1985 said mark baker attorney for 
anne henderson pollard 
pollard a 36year old former navy analyst was sentenced to 
life in prison in june 1987 after he pleaded guilty to providing 
israel with documents about the military strengths of countries in 
the middle east 
mrs pollard 30 pleaded guilty to conspiracy to receive 
embezzled government property and being an accessory to possession 
of national defense documents 
she was sentenced to five years in prison and was released this 
year after serving 40 months pollard is serving time in a maximum 
security federal prison in marion ill he is in solitary 
confinement and knows only what his father and sister tell him 
about his wifes actions baker said 
mrs pollard has worked to secure her husbands freedom since 
her release including trying to get the israeli prime minister to 
intervene on pollards behalf 
in a news release mrs pollard said she believed her husbands 
action wednesday was the result of five years of solitary 
confinement manipulation by his parents his sister and political 
forces 
i am deeply grieved by this action as i had hoped to have 
children she said 
her husbands washington lawyer judith barnett denied that 
relatives influenced his decision 
this 100 percent jonathans action she told the washington 
post 
the couple lived together for several years before being 
married in august 1985 said baker they were together as a married 
couple for just three months before they were arrested in november 
and havent seen each other since they were sentenced more than 
four years ago baker said 
mrs pollard spent a good portion of her jail term in prison 
hospitals undergoing treatment for the gastrointestinal ailment 
she is currently being treated at mount sinai hospital but hopes to 
leave for an israeli hospital where she can receive treatment at no 
cost her attorney said 
the attorney said the divorce papers were served on mrs pollard 
by a process server disguised as a hospital employee 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

