exports of us farm products declined 
seasonally in may to an estimated 326 billion but were still 
running ahead of a year earlier according to agriculture 
department analysts 
the may export estimate which was down 145 million from april 
dropped as the result of lower values for dairy products wheat 
rice grain sorghum animal feeds soybeans and cotton 
a monthly report by the departments economic research service 
said wednesday that those declines more than offset increases in 
may for corn barley live animals meat vegetable oils and 
horticultural products 
for the first eight months of the fiscal year that began last 
oct 1 however export values totaled about 285 billion up 2 
percent from the comparable period in 198889 
corn exports in may rose to 54 million metric tons valued at 
667 million the soviet union was the largest market taking 
almost 15 million tons with japan second at 12 million tons 
other major corn markets in may included mexico south korea and 
taiwan 
wheat exports dropped for the second consecutive month to 19 
million tons valued at about 294 million shipments to the soviet 
union declined sharply to 288000 tons ranking third behind china 
and japan 
soybean exports in may plummeted 48 percent in volume from april 
to 621000 tons valued at 148 million that was the lowest monthly 
volume since last september but officials said soybean shipments 
generally drop off in the second half of the fiscal year 
cotton shipments fell 20 percent in may to 128000 tons 
following a 26 percent drop in april the report said however the 
export value increased to 1628 per ton from 1573 in april 
the increase in the average cotton price was attributed to 
increased exports of higherpriced longstaple pima cotton 
declining shipments to china taiwan thailand indonesia and 
the european economic community more than offset increases to 
japan south korea hong kong and egypt the report said 
