<DOCNO> AP900719-0024 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a presidential decision to deploy the first 
phase of the strategic defense initiative in 1993 would be 
premature and fraught with high risk congressional 
investigators say 
citing design problems caused by the introduction of the 
brilliant pebbles concept of orbiting interceptors and detailed 
tests that wont be completed in time the general accounting 
office on wednesday recommended a delay in deployment of the 
antimissile system 
the report by congress watchdog agency is certain to affect 
debate over the level of spending on sdi commonly known as star 
wars the senate armed services committee in approving a 289 
billion fiscal 1991 defense bill cut 1 billion from president 
bushs 47 billion budget request for the program 
the house armed services committee which will craft its version 
of the bill later this month must slash a total of 24 billion 
from bushs overall budget of 307 billion to conform to house 
instructions a deep cut in sdi is expected 
in the report the gao said brilliant pebbles had 
drastically changed the systems design leaving it in a state of 
flux 
in january the pentagon incorporated the brilliant pebbles 
concept into phase 1 the technology involves several thousand 
interceptors that would orbit the earth to seek and destroy a 
target by smashing into it at high speeds 
the gao also said that detailed tests planned by the strategic 
defense initiative organization a defense department agency that 
oversees star wars wont be completed before the scheduled 
executive decision on deployment 
based on those problems the gao said it doesnt believe the sdi 
organization will be able to give the president enough 
information to support a 1993 decision to deploy phase 1 
the pentagon plans to spend between 69 billion and 87 billion 
to develop and deploy the first phase of sdi designed to protect 
the united states from a soviet nuclear ballistic missile attack 
defense secretary dick cheney has said the goal of phase 1 was 
to destroy half the soviet unions ss18 nuclear warheads 1540 
of the 3080 currently deployed and 40 percent of its other 
warheads launched in an initial strike against the united states 
the first phase involves seven highly integrated elements two 
spacebased sensors a spacebased weapon two groundbased 
sensors a groundbased weapon and a command and control system 
that would manage the other elements 
sdi officials believe they can support a decision to deploy 
phase 1 with less information but say it will be done at increased 
risk the gao said 
in a statement the sdi organization said its goals are to 
conduct a vigorous research and technology program that would 
be the basis for an informed decision by the president the agency 
said it would have no official comment on the report until the gao 
formally released it in early august 
rep john conyers dmich chairman of the house government 
operations committee said successful deployment depends on a 
sound stable design plan 
gaos report shows that no such plan exists because of the 
radical changes made recently by the inclusion of brilliant pebbles 
into the design caution and skepticism are appropriate when 
congress looks toward funding the completion of phase 1 said 
conyers who requested the report 
the gao noted the absence of scrutiny the pentagon envisioned 
for the program the defense acquisition board didnt conduct its 
scheduled 1989 review and has not assessed the affect of brilliant 
pebbles on the design and tests 
the lack of effective agency oversight has contributed to the 
failure of other automated weapons systems none of which matches 
the scale and technological complexity of phase 1 the gao said 
consequently any executive decision in 1993 to deploy phase 1 
would be premature and fraught with high risk 
the gao recommended that cheney advise president bush to defer a 
decision to deploy any element of the phase 1 system until the sdi 
organization has stabilized the design and shown the systems 
effectiveness through testing 
</TEXT>
