<TEXT>
us industry will be allowed to share 
technology developed in nuclear weapons laboratories as part of a 
growing governmentprivate sector partnership energy secretary 
james watkins says 
without the ability to manufacture highquality goods america 
is out of the competition watkins said as he signed two 
technologytransfer agreements with business consortia on wednesday 
the initiatives follow enactment last year of legislation 
encouraging such exchanges 
japan and a number of european countries are way ahead of us 
in government encouragement of private industry said sen carl 
levin dmich these agreements will unlock technology now in the 
hands of the government and make this country more 
competitive 
the energy departments weapons program consists of 17 
laboratories production facilities and test sites in 12 states it 
has over 100 billion in assets and a yearly research and 
development budget of about 3 billion 
the program is one of a handful in government that advance 
technology from the basic research stage all the way to product 
application it has generated some of the worlds most 
sophisticated manufacturing equipment machine tools control and 
measurement systems and quality assurance methods watkins said 
one agreement commits the energy department to share information 
with the national center for manufacturing sciences a nonprofit 
consortium based in ann arbor mich it represents more than 100 
companies 
taxpayers have invested 100 billion in americas national 
labs and production complexes over the years and they represent 
one of the worlds great treasure houses of technology and 
manufacturing knowhow said ed miller president of the center 
under the second agreement a consortium of 10 companies plus 
universities and the energy department will conduct research on 
specialty metals at the sandia national laboratories of 
albuquerque nm 
specialty metals are combinations of metals and alloys or other 
materials such as ceramics that are designed to meet strict 
qualitycontrol standards for highly complex products they are 
used in aircraft satellites nuclearpower reactors and highspeed 
drills 
the sandia lab will give industry and university researchers 
access to the only 310kilowatt electronbeam melting furnace of 
its size in the nation available for pure research 
the agreement with the center in ann arbor will boost research 
into advanced robotics techniques for manufacturing pollution 
cleanup technology and highspeed machine technology miller said 
some of the centers member companies already are working with 
the lawrence livermore national laboratory in california to develop 
a grade of aluminum that could revolutionize automobile 
production through more precise engineering miller said 
youre talking about multibilliondollar impacts to the 
productivity and quality of products he said people with the 
biggest companies in the united states general motors ford 
have already visited the laboratories and have said theyll use 
this technology if they can get access to it 
