<TEXT>
a rare cancer usually found in just 
nine of every million children struck three babies in this small 
central illinois town residents suspect an abandoned coal factory 
is to blame 
but state health officials told residents wednesday night that 
its premature to assess responsibility for the cancer cluster 
the children ranging in age from 6 months to 22 months have 
been diagnosed with neuroblastoma a cancer of the adrenal glands 
and sympathetic nervous system that occurs primarily in children 
under age 10 the sympathetic nervous system controls some 
automatic body functions 
state health experts are studying medical records and the 
incidence of cancer in taylorville a city of 11000 people about 
210 miles southwest of chicago 
the childrens parents and others in the community suspect the 
cancer cluster is linked to an abandoned factory site that was 
contaminated with coal tar the affected children all live within 
three miles of the site 
its too much to be a coincidence said brenda may whose 
7monthold daughter erika was diagnosed with neuroblastoma soon 
after birth and underwent successful surgery to remove a tumor 
a second child 22monthold zachary donaldson has been 
declared cured 6monthold chad hryhorysak is undergoing 
chemotherapy 
symptoms include weight loss body aches paleness and 
irritability in some cases tumors cause diarrhea and high blood 
pressure the condition can be fatal if left untreated but is 
usually caught in time 
residents have formed the taylorville awareness group to press 
for government investigation of the cancer cluster 
at a town meeting on the issue wednesday night state 
toxicologist tom long told residents they shouldnt blame the 
abandoned factory yet 
it is right and good for you to be concerned about the cancer 
and your environment long said however at this stage of the 
game its not right or productive to link the two 
about half of the 50 residents at the meeting signed a petition 
asking the federal centers for disease control in atlanta to 
investigate state health officials said their own investigation 
would suffice 
before the meeting mrs may said that while she was pregnant 
with erika she often took her two older daughters to play in a 
park next to the former site of a central illinois public service 
co plant that made coal gas for street lights the plant shut down 
in 1932 
thomas hornshaw who assesses toxicchemical sites for the state 
environmental protection agency said 9000 cubic yards of coal tar 
and contaminated soil were removed from the site in 1988 
although the site is no longer contaminated residents could 
have been exposed before and during the cleanup he said 
studies have linked coal tar to lung and skin cancer but not 
specifically to neuroblastoma health officials said 
mrs may said she and other parents of cancerstricken children 
are resented by some residents who fear their town will be labeled 
a cancer hazard 
but they havent stayed up all night and watched a heart 
monitor to make sure their baby is still alive she said 
in the united states neuroblastoma occurs in about nine of 
every million live births every year according to the us centers 
for disease control fewer than 500 babies are born here every year 
about 500 cases are reported each year across the country and 
the prognosis is good if the cancer is diagnosed before age 2 
researchers dont know exactly what causes neuroblastoma but 
heredity plays a role and a virus or environmental factors might be 
involved said dr holly howe chief epidemiologist for the 
illinois department of public health 
</TEXT>
