<DOCNO> AP900719-0037 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
dr karl menninger who pushed psychiatry 
into the american mainstream and for more than six decades strove 
for the compassionate treatment of the mentally ill has died at 
age 96 
the pioneer died of abdominal cancer at stormontvail regional 
medical center on wednesday just four days before his birthday 
if psychoanalysis was born in vienna the child of sigmund 
freud it grew strong on the kansas prairie under the guidance of 
menninger friends and associates said he nurtured psychiatry into 
a medical speciality 
he was one of the first american psychiatrists to integrate 
psychoanalytic theory into his practice said dr elissa benedek 
president of the american psychiatric association 
menninger was once hailed by the association as the nations 
greatest living psychiatrist a hottempered excitable 
maverick he jolted popular thought with his theories on crime 
prisons and child abuse 
menninger grew up in topeka and attended harvard medical school 
he interned at boston psychopathic hospital returning to topeka in 
1919 
in 1925 he and his father charles and brother william 
converted a 13room farmhouse into a clinic which later became the 
renowned menninger with the largest training program in the world 
for psychiatrists 
my chief purpose in the beginning was to show you could treat 
insane people menninger once recalled everybody thought 
they were untreatable but i said they were being treated every 
day we demonstrated you could treat people in a better way 
menninger applied freudian principles to people who were 
mentally ill but not psychotic said philip holzman professor of 
psychology at harvard university before that such people were not 
considered worthy of treatment he said 
he entered psychiatry at a time when psychiatry was defining 
itself holzman said 
dr gertrude ticho who worked at the menninger for 18 years and 
is now in private practice in washington said menninger was one of 
the first psychiatrists to create an environment for psychiatric 
patients based on compassion and treatment 
menningers oncerevolutionary approaches to mental illness 
became standard as psychiatrists trained at menninger established 
their own practices ticho said 
in a sense he was a victim of his own success she said 
he trained at menninger so many people who went out and set up 
comparable clinics 
in 1930 menninger published the human mind which still is 
used as a textbook in 1938 he came out with man against 
himself a seminal volume that examines patterns of 
selfdestructive behavior 
menningers other books including love against hate the 
crime of punishment and what ever became of sin also drew a 
wide readership outside of psychiatry 
dr menninger brought psychiatry to the average person 
widening public understanding and acceptance of psychiatry as an 
agent of healing and help benedek said he wrote and spoke in 
the language of the average american making mental illnesses more 
understandable and less feared 
menninger also explored the relationship between the mind and 
the body between mental health and physical wellbeing 
menninger was perhaps the foremost pioneer in refuting the 
notion of two separate systems one body the other mind in human 
beings said longtime friend norman cousins who has written 
about on health for the layman 
he advanced the concept of a singular system in which both 
mind and body were constituent parts said cousins who teaches 
at the university of california medical school 
crime and reform dominated menningers thinking in later years 
he moved to chicago in 1966 serving as a consultant on prison 
affairs and helping set up a mental health center in downtown 
chicago he moved back to topeka in 1974 
psychiatrists attribute reforms in mental hospitals to 
menninger under his guidance topeka state hospital became a 
national model for state hospitals across the country holzman said 
compassionate care of the mentally ill is the thing that 
stands out with menninger said cousins who first met menninger 
in the late 1930s all you have to do is visit a lot of mental 
hospitals to realize we have not arrived at that form of 
treatment 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

