<TEXT>
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan may 
have offered just the ingredient the administration needs to reach 
a budget deal with congress but ultimately it could poison the 
economy 
one problem is that jittery investors are reading greenspans 
pledge to lower interest rates in exchange for a budget agreement 
as a sign that the fed chief is caving in to political pressure and 
abandoning the fight against inflation 
many economists recalling the experience of the 1960s fear 
that the outcome of all the economic tinkering will be rising 
inflation and weaker growth the worst of all possible worlds and 
a prescription for the very recession the administration wants to 
avoid 
financial markets which normally rally on the promise of lower 
interest rates went into a funk after greenspans wednesday 
promise investors worried about his motivations in discussing 
lower interest rates on a day when the government was reporting a 
worrisome jump in consumer inflation 
the federal reserve as the protector of the nations money 
supply and key defender against inflation is supposed to be above 
the political fray but the timing of greenspans comments raised 
questions about whether the fed chief is now worrying more about 
his possible reappointment by president bush next year than he is 
about keeping inflation under control 
the bush administration has recently intensified its pressure on 
the greenspan fed to relent and lower interest rates the federal 
reserve had been resisting those entreaties contending that a dose 
of high interest rates was needed to slow the economy and thus 
bring inflation under control 
then suddenly last week greenspan took the unusual step of 
announcing fed intentions in advance saying that the central bank 
planned to ease credit slightly to offset overly cautious lending 
practices by the nations banks just a month ago greenspan had 
said he could not detect any broadbased tightening by lenders 
on friday the fed did ease moving to push a key interest rate 
the federal funds rate down to 8 percent it had been at 825 
percent since december 
then this week in his twiceayear appearance before congress to 
explain the feds monetary policy greenspan held out the promise 
of further interest rate declines should congress and the 
administration agree to major substantive credible cuts in the 
budget deficit 
greenspans words were hailed by the administration which wants 
fed participation in any budget deal with congress their fear is 
that the 50 billion to 60 billion in spending cuts and tax 
increases being contemplated to lower the budget deficit would take 
a lot of momentum out of an economy that is already sputtering 
along at nearrecession levels 
the economy as measured by the gross national product grew at 
a subpar 19 percent annual rate in the first three months of 1990 
and by some measurements of employment as many as 16 states are in 
a virtual recession at present 
the administration sought and got greenspans assurance that he 
would loosen monetary policy to offset the huge drop in spending 
power that would come from a deficit deal lower interest rates by 
this reasoning would give a boost to the economy by encouraging 
more business and consumer borrowing 
but what has economists concerned is that the weak growth is 
occurring at a time when inflationary pressures are rising the 
labor department reported wednesday that consumer prices shot up 
05 percent in june and have been rising at an annual rate of 59 
percent so far this year the worst price performance since former 
fed chairman paul volcker was fighting doubledigit rates at the 
beginning of the 1980s 
some economists worry that the nation may be on the verge of 
another bout of stagflation the term coined in the 1970s to 
describe a combination of slow economic growth rising prices and 
rising unemployment 
in such instances the feds ability to lower interest rates to 
boost economic growth is constrained by the need to battle 
inflation 
in addition the financial markets looking at the inflation 
numbers may resist and demand even higher interestrate premiums 
for their investments 
also policies even at the powerful federal reserve work with 
uncertain lag times and the ability to finetune monetary policy 
which is controlled by the fed and budgetary policy controlled by 
congress and the administration has not often been successful 
before 
veteran fed watchers say the last time there was an attempt at a 
coordinated hike in tax revenues and cut in interest rates came 
more than two decades ago 
president lyndon johnson pressured thenfed chairman william 
mcchesney martin to lower interest rates to offset the effects of a 
10 percent tax surchage congress enacted in 1968 to pay for the 
vietnam war 
the tax increase was not enough to offset the stimulative 
effects of the interest rate cuts thus sending inflation 
ratcheting upward and laying the groundwork for a recession which 
began at the end of 1969 ending the nations longest economic 
recovery at just over nine years 
the current recovery which is in its eighth year may be headed 
for the same fate 
there is a parallel between martins situation and greenspans 
situation said david jones chief economist at aubrey g lanston 
amp co who has written two books on fed policy if you make a 
deal with politicians there is always the danger that you will end 
up with the worst of both possible worlds you will get higher 
inflation and lower growth 
