<TEXT>
milk prices at the farm declined last winter 
but regained some of their lost ground during the spring that also 
pushed up consumer prices an agriculture department report said 
thursday 
however continued substantial growth in milk production and 
reductions in probably swollen user inventories of nonfat dry milk 
likely will limit further advances in milk and dairy product 
prices the report said 
milk production was up more than 2 percent during the apriljune 
quarter from yearearlier levels the number of cows held about 
steady but milk output per cow was up 
high farm milk prices since 1989 spurred the expansion 
although financial caution and forage concerns have restrained 
growth the report said 
milk production in the second half of 1990 probably will rise 
about 3 percent from a year earlier the report said that would 
raise total 1990 milk output by about 2 percent from last year 
if wholesale prices hold relatively steady for the rest of 1990 
analysts said the average price increase for farm milk prices may 
be in the range of 3 percent to 5 percent for the entire year 
the overall retail prices of dairy products including milk 
cheese butter and other products were up about 10 percent from a 
year earlier during the second quarter as widening price spreads 
between producers and consumers more than matched the increase in 
farm milk prices 
retail prices during the rest of 1990 likely will remain near 
recent levels and the increases from 1989 are expected to average 
8 percent to 10 percent for the year the report said 
