<TEXT>
a majority of farmers would support changes in 
federal law to help protect the nations environment a survey by a 
national conservation group said thursday 
officials of the american farmland trust said the survey 
provided strong evidence that farmers are more supportive of 
environmentally sound farming practices than their washington 
lobbyists admit 
the survey results were released as the senate began debate on 
the 1990 farm bill a complex measure that will guide us farm 
programs and policy for the next five years 
in recent months the aft said much of the debate about farm 
bill amendments has centered on alleged farmer resistance to 
changes in federal law to help clean up the environment including 
reduced use of chemicals and fertilizers 
according to the survey more than 70 percent of about 1000 
farmers interviewed in 22 states were interested in participating 
in a federal costsharing program that would reduce contamination 
of water through the adoption of new farm management practices 
further the aft said majorities of these farmers approve of 
pesticide and fertilizer use plans that would help farmers 
economize on the use of these materials 
ralph grossi president of aft a nonprofit washingtonbased 
membership organization said he gave house and senate agriculture 
committees high marks for their efforts to protect wetlands and set 
the right course on water quality planning and flexible cropland 
use 
but he added i give them very low marks on longterm soil 
protection promotion of environmentally sustainable farming and 
protection of farmland from urban encroachment 
the survey and its analysis was conducted for aft by a team at 
northern illinois university it was based on about 1000 
interviews from a data base of 1435 said spokesman david dyer 
the survey was said to have a margin error of approximately 5 
percent 
the data base was selected randomly from 42860 producers of six 
major federally supported commodities corn wheat rice cotton 
peanuts and milk in 100 counties of 22 states 
dyer said the survey was designed to reflect national attitudes 
it did not show state breakdowns 
the states where the survey was conducted are alabama arkansas 
california georgia iowa illinois indiana kansas louisiana 
michigan minnesota missouri montana north dakota nebraska new 
york ohio oklahoma pennsylvania texas washington and wisconsin 
