campaign to make children a major issue in the 1990 elections 
the american people are profoundly interested in their kids 
and the kids of this country said robert sweeney president of 
the group 
the study kids clout americans attitudes on childrens 
issues indicated that 59 percent of those polled are willing to 
have their taxes raised the estimated 100 annually it would take 
to guarantee health care for all uninsured children 
twothirds of the people asked said they would be more likely to 
vote for candidates who favor increased spending for childrens 
health care programs even if it meant a tax hike 
among occasional voters 85 percent said they would be more 
likely to vote if they thought it would have a significant impact 
on the health and welfare of american children according to the 
study 
the study is the result of a june 917 telephone survey of 1000 
adult americans conducted by washingtonbased penn amp schoen the 
polls margin of error is plus or minus 31 percent 
association officials are using the studys findings to provide 
voters with information about the status of childrens health the 
group also is urging voters to press candidates to bring childrens 
health care issues onto their platforms 
for too long children have been seen and not heard at 
election time when we decide this nations future course said 
jon vice chairman and president of childrens hospital in 
wisconsin 
the campaign i care for kids and i vote aims to increase 
funds allocated to health care programs for children such as 
medicaid by having the american public push the issue among 
candidates 
the associations campaign includes bumper stickers buttons 
booklets and handbooks and a telephone hotline 
the association of childrens hospital a nonprofit group 
founded in 1968 promotes the wellbeing of children through 
advocacy research and education 
