<TEXT>
most american employers are worried about a 
shortage of skilled workers but few have made job training for new 
employees a priority according to a study delivered to congress 
thursday 
a majority of 645 employers who were surveyed said they thought 
there was already a labor shortage in america or one on the way 
according to a study called workforce 2000 competing in a 
sellers market is corporate america prepared 
employers are specifically concerned about a potential shortfall 
of socalled knowledge workers who are professionals or have 
technical skills said the study conducted by towers perrin a 
management consultant firm 
those knowledge workers are also sometimes called gold 
collar employees because demand for them is expected to be so 
great that they will be able to name their own salaries and the 
conditions of their employment the study said those workers 
include people in such fields as electronics computers and 
communications who have technical skills 
whether or not knowledge workers will have such bargaining 
power our survey companies are clearly worried about hiring these 
important employees especially over the next five years the 
study said 
however the study said most companies are still using 
traditional solutions for recruitment or helping employees learn 
and improve skills rather than trying novel approaches 
for instance 78 percent of the firms use the traditional 
process of reimbursing employees for the costs of tuition while 
just 8 percent have their own remedial training program the study 
said 
the most common reason for rejecting potential job candidates 
was inadequate writing or verbal skills the study said but few 
firms had made training a priority 
twothirds of the firms surveyed spent less than 2000 a year 
on training for entrylevel hires and many companies spend nothing 
at all the study said 
about half of the survey respondents reported hiring more than 
150 entrylevel workers a year of those new hires about 28 
percent end up quitting or being fired within their first year 
usually because of an unacceptable job performance the study said 
the high cost of turnover notwithstanding most companies do 
not appear to be devoting significant financial resources to 
training said the study 
about 5 percent of the employers spent more than 5000 annually 
in classroom and onthejob training for new employees in their 
first year 
the study was delivered at a senate labor task force hearing on 
the workforce and workplace readiness 
sen barbara mikulski dmd who chairs the task force said 
the study reveals that most companies run their businesses like 
we were still in the 1950s 
