<TEXT>
a panel of experts recommended the food and 
drug administration turn down an application to market the nations 
first home bloodcollection kit for aids antibody testing 
the fdas blood products advisory committee on wednesday voted 
31 against approval of the proposal by university hospital 
laboratories corp of bethesda md 
with the companys test kit an individual would use a lancet to 
draw a small sample of blood which would be collected on special 
filter paper and send the sample anonymously to a laboratory where 
it would be tested the individual would receive the results by 
telephone 
panel members echoed the fdas concerns about the safety of 
people drawing their own blood and the validity of tests obtained 
through this system said dr jay s epstein chief of the 
retrovirology laboratory in fdas center for biologics evaluation 
and research 
the experts also were concerned about the adequacy of telephone 
counseling for individuals who test positive for antibodies to the 
virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome he said 
the fda is also concerned whether anonymous aidsrelated testing 
is in the public interest since public health workers would be 
unable to follow up on counseling for individuals who tested 
positive 
epstein said on thursday the fda would complete its review of 
university hospital laboratories application by aug 8 
the fda began accepting applications for aids home test kits 
last spring after officials said they would reconsider their 
opposition to home bloodcollection kits for aidsrelated testing 
university hospital laboratories application was the first 
received epstein said but he could not say how many others if 
any have been received since then 
at the time dr paul parkman director of the center for 
biologics evaluation and research said officials were persuaded to 
rethink their opposition because of medical advances in treatment 
that could slow progression of the disease in its early stages 
other considerations included technical advances that for 
example have shown accurate test results could be obtained using a 
blood sample prepared and transported on a filter paper 
university hospital laboratories had filed a lawsuit seeking to 
force the fda to accept its application which had been filed in 
december 1987 
the lawsuit was settled april 10 but fda officials said the 
lawsuit had no effect on its decision to begin accepting 
applications 
epstein said the advisory committees recommendation affected 
only university health laboratories application 
