a measles epidemic in washington state was spread 
in large part by unvaccinated immigrants who brought the virus from 
mexico federal health officials said thursday 
at least 26 percent of the 266 measles cases reported in 
washington state so far this year were acquired in mexico or were 
linked to cases acquired there the centers for disease control 
said in its weekly report 
last year 15 percent of all cases reported in the state were 
linked to mexico it said nationwide 3 percent of the 17850 
measles cases reported last year were acquired outside the united 
states it said 
across the country measles continue to be spread in medical 
settings especially hospital emergency rooms because cases often 
are not diagnosed and isolated promptly and because many medical 
workers are not immune the cdc said 
in the first 26 weeks of 1990 nearly five times more cases were 
diagnosed in washington than during all of 1989 when 55 measles 
cases were reported state health officials said the outbreak is 
the largest since 1979 
nearly half of the cases occurred among unvaccinated people the 
cdc said 
of those unvaccinated more than half were hispanics who 
account for 4 percent of the states population of 45 million and 
are its largest ethnic minority the states hispanic population 
increased by about 39 percent from 1980 to 1988 the cdc said 
detailed data available for 218 of the 266 cases showed that 97 
of them were hispanics the cdc said of those 97 cases mexican 
citizens working in washington accounted for 72 percent and 
hispanic us citizens made up 28 percent 
the state department of health spent 11 million for 76000 
doses of measles vaccine this spring said barbara baker 
washingtons immunization director 
vaccination clinics were publicized in spanish and english on 
radio and television in newspapers and by sound trucks in hispanic 
neighborhoods she said 
