<TEXT>
federal telephone regulators are warning 
foreign phone companies that if they dont stop padding charges for 
international calls the united states will take unilateral action 
to lower prices 
the federal communications commission says us phone customers 
may have paid as much as 1 billion too much for international 
calls in 1988 due to outmoded contracts that allow overseas phone 
companies to charge inflated prices for handling the other end of 
international calls 
not only does the practice hurt individual pocketbooks it adds 
greatly to the us trade deficit because far more calls go out of 
the united states than come in 
us phone companies paid out 2 billion more in 1988 than they 
took in from foreign phone companies according to the fcc which 
last thursday threatened to limit what american phone companies can 
pay to overseas carriers 
the fcc says roughly half of the 2 billion deficit represented 
an overpayment by us consumers to foreign telephone companies 
that have refused to keep prices in line with costreducing 
advances in technology such as direct dialing 
the fcc proposed to ease restrictions on how american telephone 
amp telegraph and other us longdistance companies such as mci and 
us sprint negotiate accounting rates with foreign companies 
these accounting rates determine how the two sides divvy up the 
charges consumers pay for international calls 
competition gives us companies an incentive to lower prices 
but foreign phone companies which typically are state owned dont 
face competitive pressures 
their accounting rates may be based on the cost of 
operatorassisted international calling and not reflect the lower 
costs of todays ubiquitous directdialing 
west germany for instance has not lowered its accounting rate 
since 1983 us phone companies still pay half of 156 a minute 
or 78 cents a minute to the germans for completing calls to west 
germany 
atampt and its rivals charge between 620 and 1158 for a 
10minute call from the united states to west germany depending on 
when and how the call is made but a german caller gets hit with a 
flat 1907 for the same call 
if atampt charges 62 cents a minute it loses money it makes up 
such losses however by collecting 78 cents a minute for 
completing calls from west germany to the united states 
but the inflated 156 accounting rate keeps prices high and 
customers foot the bill 
foreign governments argue that the us payments represent 
muchneeded dollars that not only subsidize local phone systems but 
also help pay for schools or imported goods 
thomas luciano deputy director for international settlements at 
atampt said wednesday that 65 percent of the us out payment goes 
to developing countries we recognize we need to be sensitive to 
the concerns of some of the foreign telephone companies were 
dealing with 
but luciano argued that if foreign nations lower their rates 
theyll more than make up the lost revenue in increased volume of 
calling both in and out of their countries lower rates also will 
boost foreign economic development he said 
luciano said atampt which has about 89 percent of the us 
overseas phone market succeeded in lowering international 
accounting rates with more than 70 nations in 1989 but he said he 
welcomed the fccs impetus 
we have already been expressing the deep concerns of the us 
government including the fcc as part of our negotiations 
luciano said 
south korea he said has reduced its accounting rate steadily 
from 236 a minute to 210 a minute and japan dropped its rates 
in 1985 from 235 to 175 a minute sweden has cut its accounting 
rate in half he added 
