<TEXT>
a federal judge who was asked to intervene 
in a bitter dispute over chippewa indian gambling in wisconsin has 
ruled that tribes that do not have gaming compacts with the state 
cannot operate casinos 
us district judge barbara crabb on wednesday denied a request 
from two chippewa bands seeking an injunction prohibiting the state 
from closing down reservation casinos that opened in the last year 
mrs crabb ruled such casino operations are and will remain 
illegal until the tribe and state negotiate and enact federally 
required gaming agreements 
but she also declared that the state which threatened to 
prosecute the tribe doesnt have authority to close down the 
operations she said that authority rests with the us attorneys 
office 
jerry maulson gaming manager for the lac du flambeau chippewa 
band that filed the lawsuit said the tribe won its argument that 
the state doesnt have jurisdiction to prosecute gambling issues on 
reservations but lost on the ruling that indian gambling was 
illegal without a gaming compact 
its sort of like a doubleedged sword maulson said 
us attorney patrick j fiedler in madison said he would 
consult with justice department officials before deciding whether 
to close any reservation casinos in wisconsin 
he said previous advice from washington indicated it was more 
sensible to rely on state prosecutors although it was believed 
the state and federal governments had concurrent jurisdiction 
the yearlong dispute in wisconsin began last fall when the 
state and its dozen indian tribes failed to reaching gambling 
regulation pacts by october as required by the us indian gambling 
regulatory act passed by congress in 1988 the government has since 
extended the deadline until next may 
the negotiations broke off late last year and tensions were 
worsened when the states top law official attorney general donald 
hanaway issued an advisory opinion in february that casino 
gambling was illegal in wisconsin 
the opinion led several local prosecutors to warn tribes they 
would raid and close down the several reservation casinos that had 
begun operations in the last year 
most of the tribes closed their reservations voluntarily but 
two bands of chippewas sued asking mrs crabb to stop the state 
from enforcing state gambling laws on the reservations 
mrs crabb denied the request saying the tribes could avoid 
prosecution by the government by not sponsoring casino operations 
until the required gaming compacts are enacted 
the ruling came a day after interior secretary manuel lujan 
announced guidelines that would allow tribes to buy nonreservation 
land to open bingo parlors and other gaming establishments 
under the guidelines such purchases would have to be approved 
by the governor of the state lujan said 
the guidelines also bar tribes from buying outofstate land for 
gambling sites the interior department will seek input from tribes 
before putting the guidelines in effect 
