<DOCNO> AP900719-0158 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the minnesota supreme court overturned a 
700000 damage award to a man who sued the states two largest 
daily newspapers for revealing his identity after he was promised 
anonymity 
in a 42 decision to be filed friday the states highest court 
said the saint paul pioneer press and the star tribune of 
minneapolis could not be held liable for breaking reporters 
promises of confidentiality to dan cohen in 1982 
the ruling which one attorney called a major victory for 
news organizations upheld a state appeals court panels dismissal 
of cohens claim of fraudulent misrepresentation but reversed that 
courts ruling allowing his breachofcontract claim 
to impose a contract theory on this arrangement puts an 
unwarranted legal rigidity on a special ethical relationship 
precluding necessary consideration of factors underlying that 
ethical relationship associate justice john simonett wrote for 
the majority 
the court also said enforcement of the promise of 
confidentiality under a doctrine that implies a legal contract 
where none exists in fact would violate the newspapers first 
amendment rights 
cohens attorney elliot rothenberg said thursday the case will 
be appealed to the us supreme court 
this case isnt over by a long shot rothenberg said 
its a very important case one with farreaching 
implications he said the issue is to what extent do 
newspapers and the media have a constitutional right to violate 
promises to which everyone else in society would be held liable 
attorneys for the associated press which filed the only 
friendofthecourt brief in the case said cohens trial court 
victory had produced a spate of similar lawsuits around the country 
the latest decision is the first definitive opinion by a 
supreme court of a state directly addressing the issues in 
cohens case and one in which the news media can take 
considerable comfort said attorney dick winfield of the rogers 
and wells law firm in new york the aps general counsel 
louise sommers also of rogers and wells said the ruling was a 
major victory for the news media 
the newspapers and the ap were able to convince the supreme 
court that the first amendment mattered in a case like this where 
a source who had grounds to sue for conventional libel chose to 
mask it as a breachofcontract suit she said 
the case stemmed from a 1982 incident in which cohen gave 
reporters copies of court documents showing that marlene johnson 
then seeking her first term as lieutenant governor had been 
convicted of shoplifting 12 years earlier 
johnsons conviction was vacated in 1971 with no sentence she 
was elected as democratic gov rudy perpichs running mate in 1982 
reelected in 1986 and is running with perpich this year 
cohen who was doing public relations work for 1982 republican 
gubernatorial candidate wheelock whitney provided information 
about johnson on condition he not be identified 
reporters for the newspapers gave him that assurance but 
editors decided to name cohen as their source of the documents 
editors testified that they named cohen because they felt the 
public had a right to know the information came from the whitney 
campaign 
reporters for the ap and wccotv also promised cohen anonymity 
and received the documents the ap published the story and honored 
its promise while the television station did not run the story 
cohen claimed in his lawsuit that he lost his advertising agency 
job after the newspapers breached an oral contract to keep his name 
out of the story 
in rejecting cohens argument that contract law should apply to 
his case the supreme court majority said we are not persuaded 
that in the special milieu of media newsgathering a source and a 
reporter ordinarily believe they are engaged in making a legally 
binding contract 
they are not thinking in terms of offers and acceptances in 
any commercial or business sense the majority said the 
parties understand that the reporters promise of anonymity is 
given as a moral commitment but a moral obligation alone will not 
support a contract 
in addressing whether a promise of confidentiality might 
otherwise be enforceable the court said it had to balance the 
constitutional rights of a free press against the commonlaw 
interest of protecting a promise of anonymity 
of critical significance in this case is the fact that the 
promise of anonymity arises in the classic first amendment context 
of the quintessential public debate in our democratic society 
namely a political source involved in a political campaign the 
court said 
the potentiality for civil damages for promises made in this 
context chills public debate a debate which cohen willingly 
entered albeit hoping to do so on his own terms in this context 
and considering the nature of the political story involved it 
seems to us that the law best leaves the parties here to their 
trust in each other 
in his dissent associate justice lawrence yetka said the result 
of the majority opinion was to carve out yet another special 
privilege in favor of the press that is denied other citizens 
associate justice glenn kelley who joined yetkas dissent said 
the decision serves to inhibit rather than to promote the 
objectives of the first amendment by drying up potential sources 
of information on public matters 
chief justice peter popovich took no part in the decision 
saint paul pioneer press attorney paul hannah said the courts 
majority recognized the difficulties editors and reporters face in 
making decisions about what voters are going to know about the 
candidates and campaigns 
star tribune executive editor joel r kramer said in a statement 
for release friday that the newspaper was especially pleased that 
the court has ruled that the decision to publish true facts 
relating to the activities of a political source in a political 
campaign is one that is protected by the first amendment 
the court following its policy allowed attorneys in the case 
to be contacted thursday but forbade contacts with parties in the 
case until friday 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

