<TEXT>
the manslaughter conviction of an 
electrician whose faulty work caused a fatal fire has left other 
electricians worried that honest mistakes could lead to criminal 
prosecution 
richard e salz 49 of east haven was convicted june 1 and 
faces sentencing friday in superior court for seconddegree 
manslaughter in the fire death of a 12yearold boy he faces a 
maximum sentence of 10 years in prison 
phil simmons executive director of the park ridge illbased 
international association of electrical contractors said he knew 
of no other case in which an electrician has been charged with 
manslaughter for a death resulting from his work 
the boy burton gorman iii died of smoke inhalation in a dec 
28 1988 house fire caused by a baseboard heating unit that salz 
had improperly installed the month before 
besides failing to get a permit for the work salz ignored the 
manufacturers instructions for installing the heater and committed 
more than a dozen electrical code violations witnesses at his 
trial said 
salz connected the 120volt heater to a 240volt circuit box 
doubling the amount of heat that was supposed to come from the 
heater witnesses said when the unit overheated it ignited the 
wall paneling 
lou acampora president of the connecticut electrical 
contractors association said that while salz had shown a total 
disregard for safety the conviction set a bad precedent 
it puts a lot of good electricians in jeopardy for making a 
mistake said acampora who said the heads of trade groups in 
neighboring new york also had expressed concern about the ruling 
the case also has drawn the attention of electricians in other 
parts of the country said simmons a former chief electrical 
inspector for the state of washington 
i hope it has a sobering effect and that people realize they 
will be held responsible for their actions he said 
authorities involved in the prosecution said the fears of a 
precedent are unfounded they say salz who at one time worked as a 
parttime electrical inspector was charged only because he 
recklessly took actions he should have known would cause a fire 
hazard 
this was not just john q public making an honest mistake 
said lawrence acquarulo an assistant state building inspector who 
testified at salzs jury trial 
salzs license as a contractor was revoked in july 1989 but the 
state electrical work examining board this spring gave him a 
journeymans license allowing him to work under supervision 
