<TEXT>
a confessed killer who was 
acquitted because of a typing error in a police report will not be 
retried 
palm beach circuit judge marvin mounts on wednesday dismissed a 
firstdegree murder charge against frank mr lucky mars ending 
years of legal wrangling over the case 
in 1983 mars confessed to murdering a friend but was acquitted 
because the time of death listed in a legal document submitted as 
evidence was off by 12 hours 
the document said mars shot willie berry between 5 oclock 
pm january 29 1983 and 1259 am january 30 1983 
the entry should have read 1259 pm 
testimony presented by prosecutors showed that berry could not 
have been killed until after 130 am when he left a party with 
mars to buy cigarettes 
when prosecutors sought to retry the case with corrected 
documents the defense cited doublejeopardy objections and mounts 
agreed 
the case was appealed to the florida supreme court and the 11th 
us circuit court of appeals which in march upheld mounts 
decision 
he dismissed the charge wednesday 
you cant let your personal beliefs make your ruling he 
said the ruling must be based on the law 
mars attorneys hailed the decision as a simple defense of a 
basic constitutional right the double jeopardy clause of the fifth 
amendment provides that a person cannot be tried twice for the same 
offense 
they were seeking to put my client in the electric chair 
said assistant public defender cherry grant im sorry but if 
youre going to kill someone youd better dot all your is and 
cross all your ts 
mars is scheduled for release in 1991 from glades correctional 
institution where he is imprisoned for violating the terms of 
parole on an earlier conviction 
