officials will travel to luanda on saturday the department said 
despite the urgency of providing food in both government and 
rebelheld territory international relief efforts have been 
stalled by disagreement between the warring sides over supply 
routes 
several international donors have revoked their pledges because 
of backlogs at angolas ports and pilfering of relief supplies 
the international committee of the red cross leading the relief 
project has decided that airlifts are too expensive and is trying 
to arrange safe passage through land corridors for trucks 
the organization estimates 250000 people are in immediate need 
and hundreds of thousands more are in less dire straits 
angolas government wants the food delivered via port namibe on 
its western coast and from there trucked to government and rebel 
areas 
the unita rebels led by us protege jonas savimbi want the 
food delivered through namibia and botswana which border territory 
it controls in southern angola but the angolan government says it 
is worried weapons could be smuggled to the rebels with the food 
