an advisory committee told the federal government 
it should tighten the standard for safe levels of lead in blood 
new research shows that even low levels of lead in the blood 
contribute to childhood learning disabilities and high school 
dropout rates the 14member committee told the atlantabased 
centers for disease control on tuesday 
currently the cdcs standard calls for medical intervention and 
environmental controls when someones blood contains 25 or more 
micrograms per deciliter 
the committee recommended continuing the standard for medical 
intervention but said environmental controls should be considered 
whenever screening shows a level of 10 micrograms per deciliter in 
children said dr paul mushak a professor of environmental 
pathology at the university of north carolina 
