<TEXT>
lady ashton better known as madge garland who 
was fashion editor of english vogue in the 1930s and founded the 
royal college of arts fashion school has died according to news 
reports wednesday she was 92 
she had been cared for at a london convent in recent years and 
died sunday the times of london reported it gave no cause of 
death and funeral details were not announced 
she was born madge mcharg on june 12 1898 in melbourne 
australia where her father was in business she grew up in london 
and became a journalist in the 1920s first working for english 
vogue with novelist aldous huxley and photographer cecil beaton 
and later freelancing for womens wear daily in the united states 
her friends included the couturier paul poiret and the sculptor 
brancusi she chose clothes for virginia woolf artists marie 
laurencin and edward wolfe painted her and she was one of beatons 
earliest subjects 
she returned to english vogue as fashion editor from 1933 
bringing readers the best of paris fashion until world war ii 
she became merchandising manager for londons main department 
store bourne and hollingsworth during the war and designed some 
fashion after the war she visited the united states to study 
readytowear marketing methods for the british fashion industry 
in 1947 sir robin darwin of the royal college of art invited 
her to found the first british school of fashion as professor 
garland she opened the school the following year and remained at 
its head until 1956 designers david sassoon and gina fratini were 
among her students 
during the 1960s she produced five books on fashion beauty and 
the history of costumes 
she was married briefly in the 1920s to capt ewart garland in 
1953 she married sir leigh ashton then director of victoria and 
albert museum the marriage lasted less than a year although they 
were not divorced until 1962 she retained the name lady ashton for 
formal purposes 
she had no children 
</TEXT>
