<TEXT>
the biggest companies seem to make the biggest 
news in the stock market and for obvious reasons they and their 
products are known to the public and their stocks make up the 
popular averages and indices 
but the biggest companies are not a proxy for the economy as a 
whole as a number of smallbusiness and mediumsize business 
groups feel compelled to point out from time to time 
what happens to the biggest names in corporate america can be 
and often is at variance with what is happening in the rest of the 
economy and evidence of that is contained in the latest dividend 
actions 
many of the biggest companies have been raising dividends the 
smaller companies have tended to stay put with relatively few of 
them taking positive action such as resuming dividends raising 
them and adding extras 
observe the contrast 
in the first half of 1990 cash dividends paid by companies 
making up the standard amp poors 500stock index rose 12 percent 
for the 12 months through june the same companies paid out 56 
percent of profits as dividends 
that latter figure say researchers at wright investors 
service compares with just 49 percent for the past decade and 51 
percent for the period 19501989 
figures of that sort suggest a high level of management 
confidence among the larger companies since companies looking for 
a downturn arent likely to commit themselves to larger payouts 
now enlarge the measurement to 10000 companies among these 
companies which make up the entire sampp universe only 868 took 
positive dividend action in the first six months of the year down 
25 percent from a year earlier 
says wright this is the lowest number of positive dividend 
actions in the first half of any year since 1971 a fact which 
illustrates corporate managements lack of confidence regarding the 
nearterm profit outlook 
the contrast with the bigger companies becomes even sharper on 
further examination 
according to wright the total of 187 dividend cuts and 
omissions in the first half of the year was more than 70 percent 
higher than in the first half of 1989 and the highest sixmonth 
total of unfavorable actions since 1983 
other studies have shown similar disparities between the 
performance and expectations of smaller and larger companies 
in contrast to a longterm trend for example the performance 
of smallcompany stocks has lagged behind that of bigger companies 
since 1983 casting much doubt about the veracity of the socalled 
smallstock effect 
smallcompany stocks according to that theory have a tendency 
to outperform larger companies one factor being that good small 
companies have the ability to grow at a faster rate than 
ponderously large operations 
other factors enter the picture as well smallcompany stocks 
are often run by the original entrepreneur who understands the 
company and demands nothing but the best and unexamined by 
analysts smallcompany stocks are more likely to be undervalued 
their prices exploding when they are finally discovered 
in recent months some analysts say they are seeing signs of a 
recovery by the smaller stocks but if dividend actions are an 
indicator similar signs are hardly evident among the larger stocks 
the dividend yield on the sampp 500 stock index recently was 33 
percent or well below its longterm average yield of 42 percent 
such figures suggest that bigcompany stocks might be overpriced 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900719-0195 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
kuwaitis are debating how to pursue democracy four 
years after the ruling family closed the westernstyle parliament 
and press 
some feel the choice for the emirate where oil provides one of 
the worlds highest per capita incomes is between reviving the old 
system and developing an islamic brand of democracy 
the government and dissidents have traded accusations of blame 
for setbacks to the democratic institutions but dissident leader 
ahmed alsaadoun said our loyalty to our leader the emir is 
undiminished by our unrelenting struggle for democracy 
security authorities have tried to cast an undue tinge of 
rebellion on our movement saadoun speaker of the dissolved 
parliament said in an interview riot police ruthlessly 
dispersed peaceful rallies closed our diwaniyas and arrested 
parliament deputies 
diwaniyas are informal gatherings at the homes prominent 
citizens to discuss current issues the government declared the 
diwaniyas of former deputies illegal at one point and ordered them 
closed 
dissidents and witnesses said police used clubs and tear gas to 
disperse prodemocracy demonstrators they said some members of the 
former parliament were beaten up and 15 were arrested 
the respected institution of diwaniya has been badly abused 
sheik salem alsabah the interior minister told reporters the 
diwaniya became a platform of diatribe and antigovernment 
agitation we had to put an end to that 
about 30 of the 50 former deputies under saadoun lead a 
prodemocracy movement that has broad support among wealthy 
merchants in the persian gulf emirate 
native kuwaitis are the largest minority in our own country 
and with the population structure being infested with all kinds of 
hostile and begrudging elements we desperately need national unity 
today more than ever before said mohammed alqadiri a close 
aide of saadoun 
fewer than 40 percent of the emirates 18 million people are 
kuwaitis about 30 percent of the residents are shiite moslems 
some of whom sympathize with the islamic revolution in nearby iran 
kuwait once had the arab worlds only free press and freely 
elected parliament both of which were eyed with suspicion by 
neighboring saudi arabia and other conservative regimes in the gulf 
region 
when the iraniraq war began in 1980 the government decided 
democracy was a luxury no persian gulf nation could afford 
proiranian shiites spread terror in kuwait with bombings and made 
a daring attempt to kill the emir 
relations between kuwait and iran have improved since a 
ceasefire halted the war in 1988 and foreign minister ali akbar 
velayati of iran visited recently 
several times during the war the press and parliament 
embarrassed the government with accusations of corruption and open 
debates of subversion and foreign policy 
criticism of the government became increasingly harsh after the 
unofficial souk almanakh stock market collapsed in 1982 the press 
also blamed the government for the crash which was worthless 
postdated checks totaling 97 billion 
deputies claimed the government had allowed influential people 
close to the ruling sabah family to borrow speculation money from 
banks without collateral 
that prompted the emir sheik jaber alahmed alsabah to 
suspend the national assembly in 1986 and censor the press 
the emir acted on his constitutional authority when he 
dissolved parliament but the constitutional stipulation that 
elections for a new parliament be held within 60 days was 
ignored saadoun said 
on july 9 sheik jaber ordered the detainees freed and 
introduced a transitional legislature dissidents rejected as 
unconstitutional jaber said the 75member national council would 
pave the way for a parliament within four years 
he ordered the council of 50 elected and 25 appointed members to 
create controls to avert the acrimony that precipitated two 
suspensions of parliament in a decade 
saadoun and other activists expressed fear the government would 
amend the constitution to curtail the powers of parliament 
this rape of democracy cannot be tolerated he said all 
nonconstitutional action including the current national council 
must be abolished without delay 
the emir has spoken of eventual return to a desired 
parliament which was widely interpreted as return to a 
westernstyle body 
several activists believe however that jaber might opt for an 
islamictype shura consultative council rather than a genuine 
legislature which would please theocratic saudi arabia and other 
conservative arab states 
</TEXT>
