<DOCNO> AP900719-0196 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the economy is in shambles after 15 years 
of civil war and president elias hrawi has gone on the road 
seeking at least 20 billion in foreign aid to rescue it 
one safeguard against total economic collapse is lebanons gold 
reserves of about 32 billion but falling gold prices have cost 
the treasury about 500 million in the past 18 months the national 
debt is estimated at 23 billion 
onethird of the bullion is stored at fort knox ky and the 
rest in underground central bank vaults in moslem west beirut 
foreign currency reserves held by the central bank virtually 
the only state institution that still functions have declined to 
650 million from 1 billion in december heavy fighting early this 
year drove down the lebanese pound and the bank sold some reserves 
to support the currency 
hrawi has been touring arab capitals in search of financial aid 
and a threemember arab league committee entrusted with ending the 
war is trying to raise 2 billion for lebanon 
premier salim hoss an economist and former banker said 2 
billion would be barely enough to reconstruct the 
infrastructure of an economy that once was the most flourishing 
in the middle east 
lebanese economists estimate reconstruction will cost at least 
21 billion but many put the figure higher 
citizens of lebanon are believed to have about 30 billion in 
assets outside the country bankers believe an end to the 
christianmoslem war which has cost an estimated 150000 lives 
since 1975 would bring much of it back 
a settlement remains elusive despite a peace plan mediated by 
the arab league and endorsed by lebanons parliament and the 
election of hrawi in october to implement it 
the long war has devastated the lebanese pound it was 25 to 
the dollar 15 years ago but hit 690 to the dollar in june 
all the several dozen banks in beirut speculate on the volatile 
lebanese money market they buy pounds if they believe things will 
improve even for a short time and dollars when they expect bad 
news 
even the central bank plays the market it uses the profits to 
finance the budget because government revenues have virtually 
disappeared 
revenue from customs levies collapsed when militias took over 
ports operating them illegally and even built their own ports 
the cost to the treasury is about 200 million a year 
prices are soaring in a country that imports at least 85 percent 
of its necessities precise statistics are rare but economists and 
bankers estimate the annual inflation rate at 400 percent 
the general federation of labor unions which represents 250000 
workers puts unemployment at 47 percent and says most people with 
jobs must moonlight to make ends meet 
lebanon has no social welfare system so the unemployed rely on 
working relatives leave the country resort to crime or join 
militias 
fierce fighting in the past 18 months between christians and 
syrians and between rival christian forces have taken a terrible 
economic toll 
artillery battles destroyed or damaged hundreds of factories an 
shops a un report in june said fighting between christians that 
began jan 30 had caused damage totaling 500 million 
unprecedented damage to electricity water and 
telecommunications systems has directly affected 15 million people 
seriously affecting all social and economic life it said 
last month economist marwan iskandar predicted economic and 
social catastrophe unless effective action was taken in the next 
few months 
iskandar writing in the independent annahar daily urged the 
government to sell its gold reserves and invest the money in 
european government bonds to bring in about 350 million a year 
he said government spending should be limited to that amount and 
such stateowned utilities as power plants water oil refineries 
and communications systems should be sold to private investors 
finance minister ali khalil noted that four years ago the 
parliament forbade the sale of bullion because we feared that 
replacing gold with foreign currencies would open the door wide to 
government spending 
beirut was the middle easts banking capital before the war 
bustling with western tycoons and arab oil sheiks 
when the israeli army invaded in 1982 billions of dollars in 
arab assets held in lebanon fled to europe even now most of the 
several dozen lebanese banks keep up to 90 percent of their assets 
liquid 
lebanons economy has been cushioned by aid from arab and other 
countries and by large amounts of money given the militias by 
foreign backers including syria libya iraq iran israel and the 
palestine liberation organization 
economists estimated there are 80000 armed irregulars in 
lebanon 
another source of invisible income is the trade in opium and 
hashish grown in the syriancontrolled bekaa valley of east 
lebanon which earns about 200 million a year for the growers 
</TEXT>
