<DOCNO> AP900719-0199 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president alan garcia will leave office 
saturday in disgrace having presided over the most disastrous 
economic decline in perus 169year history but he may be back 
many politicians and analysts think he plans to seek the 
presidency again in 1995 after sitting out a term because peruvian 
presidents cannot serve consecutive terms 
alan garcia is a firstrate politician said independent 
congressman alfredo barnechea a former ally hes a man full of 
political resources and talents 
barnechea is skeptical of garcias chances however because of 
the liberal freemarket revolution spreading over the world 
garcia has entered a hard rock disco singing boleros from the 
1950s said barnechea who quit the presidents centerleft 
aprista party and is allied with the more conservative democratic 
front at some point the people are going to realize this 
when he took office five years ago garcia was 36 years old 
6foot3 with a baby face the youngest president on the continent 
some called him the john f kennedy of latin america because of 
his youth and the hope his populism inspired 
his waist has thickened since 1985 and his speeches draw more 
jeers than applause one pundit described him as less the kennedy 
of the region than the elvis presley 
garcias most publicized actions were limiting payments on the 
foreign debt to 10 percent of foreign earnings then stopping all 
payments he used the money to finance a dramatic shortlived 
economic expansion 
as the boom slowed the government was plagued by labor strife 
leftist insurgencies and an elephantine bureaucracy that gobbled up 
intis the peruvian currency as fast as they were printed 
garcias popularity plummeted 
during his term inflation totaled 2 million percent and 10000 
people were killed in a spreading guerrilla war 
fourfifths of peruvian workers do not have steady jobs the 
nation owes 20 billion abroad and is isolated from international 
lenders 
on two occasions garcia fended off coup threats by the 
military at one point in 1988 he did not leave the government 
palace for 34 straight days and offered his resignation to vice 
president luis alberto sanchez who was 88 years old and blind 
sanchez refused it 
an understanding of the aprista party is necessary to any 
assessment of garcias potential appeal and chances of a comback 
barnechea said 
it is officially called apra for american popular revolutionary 
alliance and was founded in 1924 as a noncommunist alternative to 
the antiimperialist left and antielitist middle class 
the party won elections in 1962 but the military prevented it 
from taking power in 1985 garcia became the first aprista 
president 
apra became perus bestorganized party during 61 years of 
opposition with its own flag and anthem many of those years were 
spent underground with the party leaders in exile 
barnechea described apra as a complex institution that had 
lost its sense of political identity 
like all mythologies it exists at a distance from reality 
he said the victory or failure of its deeds have no relation to 
the rise or fall in the faith of its followers 
he said the partys 20 percent of the vote in the first round of 
the 1990 presidential election came mostly from party diehards and 
its perfectly conceivable garcia believes this to be a good 
start for a presidential campaign in 1995 
garcia regained his stride and some of his popularity in the 
1990 campaign although aprista candidate luis alva castro was 
eliminated in the first round the president remained a factor in 
the runoff between centrist alberto fujimori and novelist mario 
vargas llosa a champion of free markets 
he used the government newspaper and television station as well 
as pagina libre a new lima newspaper in which he is said to hold a 
major share to attack vargas llosas economic shock proposals 
fujimori won the june 10 election in a landslide and garcia 
quickly claimed the victory 
mr fujimori represents the negation of everything the other 
candidate stood for he said the voters said no to liberalism 
no to the right im totally identified with the feeling behind 
that vote 
since the election fujimori has slowly warmed to the idea of an 
economic shock and has begun mending fences with foreign lenders 
the new president has said he will dismantle garcias price subsidy 
programs and controls on currency exchange rates 
the shift by fujimori leaves garcia an opening to lead the 
opposition which analysts say would help his chances in 1995 if 
the new government falters 
alberto fujimori shouldnt forget his commitment and 
responsibility is first with perus poor majority said an 
unsigned editorial in pagina libre that many believe garcia wrote 
political commentator fernando rospigliosi wrote of garcia in 
the news magazine caretas between being the head of the 
opposition or an ally with the government theres no doubt which 
role he would prefer 
</TEXT>
