<TEXT>
the first nest ever reported in washington 
of a bird called a marbled murrelet has been found in oldgrowth 
hemlock cheering ornithologists and stirring new questions about 
logging of oldgrowth forests 
thats really exciting news said jim pissot executive 
director of the audubon society of washington 
he said it will strengthen the societys drive to see the chubby 
little shorebird listed as threatened by the us fish and wildlife 
service 
the bird is fairly common elsewhere and little is known about 
its nesting habits but the audubon petition filed in january 
1988 contends mounting biological evidence shows logging of 
coastal oldgrowth forests threatens the birds nesting habitat 
logging of millions of acres of public oldgrowth forest in 
washington oregon and california already is threatened since the 
fish and wildlife service declared the northern spotted owl a 
threatened species the owl nests in oldgrowth forest 
federal officials are working out a management plan to protect 
the owl and still take into account the affect on timber 
communities officials say reductions proposed in a federal 
scientific report could mean the loss of more than 20000 jobs over 
the next decade 
the murrelet nest containing one chick was found last week by 
state department of wildlife researcher tom hamers roughly 25 miles 
inland from port susan in snohomish county department spokesman 
john pierce said wednesday 
its parents apparently visit the nest only at dawn and dusk to 
feed the chick he said 
i cant tell you how exciting this is although weve had egg 
fragments turned in and fledglings found in the forest this is the 
first nest found after years and years of searching he said 
pierce said the only other marbled murrelet nest found this year 
was in oregons siuslaw national forest 
little is known about the nesting behavior of the brown and 
white robinsize murrelet according to a recent study by the 
state department of wildlife 
ornithologists have searched for its nests throughout its 
range from central california to the bering sea and from kamchatka 
soviet union to northern japan yet only 13 nests have been 
found said the study written by lora l leschner and eric b 
cummins 
the nests that have been found and recent discoveries of 
marbled murrelets at inland locations in oregon and california 
indicate that the species may be traveling inland to nest in 
oldgrowth forests leschner and cummins wrote 
the harvest of the last of the oldgrowth forests in coastal 
washington oregon and california and the increased harvest of 
oldgrowth in british columbia and alaska could pose a serious 
threat to marbled murrelet populations they said 
