<TEXT>
the revco drugstore chain was an ignominious 
groundbreaker in 1988 when it became the first company to file for 
bankruptcy court protection after a billiondollar takeover 
financed with junk bonds 
now another precedent could be emerging from the tangled mess of 
revco ds inc an examiner appointed by the bankruptcy court said 
this week the companys creditors may have grounds to sue 
shareholders investment bankers and other parties to recover 
losses caused by the 1986 leveraged buyout 
the report by examiner barry l zaretsky will only be used as an 
advisory opinion by the judge overseeing revcos reorganization 
but the opinion if it eventually finds its way into the law could 
have a chilling effect on other companies and other takeovers 
in his report zaretsky said that under the laws of michigan 
where revco is incorporated creditors might be able to sue because 
of the socalled fraudulent conveyance of the company 
the conveyance occurred when shareholders sold the company to 
the managementled investor group that engineered the 15 billion 
lbo 
a fraudulent conveyance is a transaction made without fair 
consideration if the debtor is rendered insolvent or is left with 
unreasonably small capital said zaretsky a professor at 
brooklyn law school in new york 
zaretsky admits litigation is no panacea for those waiting to 
paid but considering the rash of failed takeovers during the past 
year the prospect of a new avenue of redress for a firms 
creditors is nonetheless appealing 
in considering who might be liable to revco creditors zaretsky 
notes that investment bankers and others who helped arrange the 
buyout were paid 80 million in fees an amount he called grossly 
disproportionate to the benefit if any received by revco 
if investment firms could be held liable for the failed buyouts 
they arrange they might worry more about the ultimate success of 
the deals than with the fees they stood to make 
zaretsky stressed in his report that his conclusions were 
tentative and based on an asyet uncompleted examination of revcos 
problems 
but he said he has found a basis for proving the financial 
elements of a fraudulent conveyance and that revco was left 
with insufficient capital to conduct its business 
he also found evidence the leveraged buyout rendered revco 
insolvent 
in reaching his conclusions the examiner cited among other 
factors the impact on revcos business of loan agreements reached 
in the buyout process 
zaretsky also found fault with financial forecasts used by 
proponents of the buyout 
reasonable projections based on the same assumptions as those 
used in projections made available to the examiner would have shown 
that revco was left with insufficient capital to satisfy its then 
known obligations he said 
zaretskys findings were filed with the us bankruptcy court in 
akron ohio which is handling the revco case revco headquartered 
in twinsburg ohio filed for protection from its creditors after 
it missed an interest payment on 700 million in junk bonds used to 
finance the lbo 
zaretsky admits he has raised more questions than he has answers 
for calling remedies for creditors under a fraudulent conveyance 
suit largely virgin territory he said he would do further 
research before making recommendations on just who should pay and 
how 
however he said the courts could fashion an equitable remedy 
which would allow unsecured general creditors to be paid in full 
with interest at the expense of the parties who contributed to the 
fraudulent conveyance 
several times in his report zaretsky stated that negotiations 
between revco and its creditors would be a better means of 
resolving the situation although the talks have been bogged down 
for some time the examiner advised the court to bring in a 
mediator to hasten the processs 
if a reorganization plan for the company is not in the offing by 
november when statutes of limitations in the case are about to 
expire zaretsky warned he is likely to recommend the 
commencement of fraudulent conveyance litigation as well as suits 
on several other grounds 
it is possible he is raising the specter of a lawsuit as a way 
to get the parties off the dime zaretsky warned that if new 
litigation is spawned it will be a long process with uncertain 
results and it may take a further toll on revcos business 
</TEXT>
