<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission says it 
supports new restrictions on the multibilliondollar business of 
advising people how to invest their money but says it could do 
more with more money 
sec commissioner mary l schapiro told a house panel wednesday 
that the commission now favors legislation requiring tougher sec 
registration requirements rather than farming out responsibility to 
an independent selfregulating organization 
she said the sec believed direct sec regulation of investment 
advisers is preferable to selfregulation 
last year the sec submitted legislation that would give 
investment adviser oversight to a selfregulatory organization such 
as the national association of securities dealers which oversees 
the overthecounter market 
but in testimony before the finance subcommittee of the house 
energy and commerce committee ms schapiro said the sec 
relunctantly lent its support to industry selfregulation because 
it didnt have the money to adequately police the industry and 
didnt think it was going to get more money soon 
she called for increasing registration fees investment advisers 
pay the sec and earmarking the money for enforcement the sec now 
does not keep any of the money it collects in fees but must turn 
it over to the treasury department for general government spending 
rep rick boucher dva a member of the subcommittee has 
submitted a bill that would require anyone offering investment 
advice for pay to register with the sec whether they call 
themselves an investment adviser or a financial planner 
they would be required to provide clients with accurate 
information the bill also would give customers the right to sue 
for damages when they lose money because of violations of the law 
bouchers bill would not increase sec fees however 
the bill also would continue the exemption from registration now 
in effect for banks as well as lawyers accountants and other 
professionals who give investment advice only as a sideline 
ms schapiro said she had no problem with that but others did 
mary a malgoire of the national association of personal 
financial advisors a professional association of planners that 
earn only fees not commissions opposed the exemptions for 
lawyers and accountants 
she said such professionals if not registered with sec would 
not be subject to financial planning oversight from state licensing 
boards 
outside the hearing room ms schapiro told reporters the sec 
currently spends 57 million annualy on registering and reviewing 
investment advisers 
to do everything recommended in a general accounting office 
report on investment adviser regulation she said the agency would 
have to spend an additional 17 million 
in a report issued monday the gao the accounting arm of 
congress warned that investors may be lulled into a false sense of 
security because investment advisers must register with the sec 
although the agency does not evaluate adviser competence 
the gao study noted that since 1980 the number of investment 
advisers has tripled to about 14000 while assets they manage have 
increased from 440 billion 10 years ago to about 46 trillion 
today 
the gao also found the sec was behind in reviewing registered 
advisers when advisers are reviewed usually only inadequate 
disclosure or recordkeeping problems are uncovered and the sec 
does little to ensure that deficiencies are corrected the report 
said 
sec oversight provides investors little assurance that the 
information they receive from advisers is accurate or that advisers 
operate in accordance with the law according to the gao study 
the gao recommended that the sec inspect all newly registered 
advisers within a year and periodically thereafter 
the sec however noted that to implement the reports 
recommendations would require tripling the 53person staff now 
devoted to investment adviser review 
ms schapiro began her testimony by defending the secs track 
record and noting the gao report said virtually all of its 
important recommendations for a more effective adviser regulatory 
program could only be implemented in the commissioner were given 
significant additional resources 
