<TEXT>
a teamsters union threat to call a 
nationwide strike against united parcel service of america inc 
marks the second round of difficult contract negotiations between 
the two sides in less than a decade 
the union said it may strike if a new threeyear contract isnt 
approved by july 31 the day the old threeyear pact expires a ups 
spokesman said wednesday 
we have been informed by the union leadership that if it is 
rejected that is their intent said the spokesman ken sternad 
we think weve made a very good offer 
sternad said 140000 to 150000 parttime and fulltime ups 
employees are teamsters members the company employs 230000 
workers 
repeated calls to the teamsters union office in washington 
dc and the local office were not returned 
when the deadline passed during national negotiations in 1982 
and talks were extended ups informed its customers that it would 
stop picking up packages said paul r schlesinger an analyst with 
donaldson lufkin amp jenrette securities corp in new york 
it was in essence a lockout the teamsters quickly got 
rightthinking and there was a settlement schlesinger said 
he said a strike wasnt likely partly because both sides would 
have too much to lose 
the teamsters have the ability to hurt ups badly ups has the 
ability to take the teamsters out completely he said adding 
that there are more teamsters at ups than at any other company 
ballots were mailed during the weekend so union members could 
vote on the proposed contract sternad said 
he said the proposal calls for higher wages improved benefits 
and better working conditions adding that the union members are 
already the highest paid of any teamsters in the country 
ups is the worlds no 1 package delivery service it made 28 
billion deliveries last year for a record 124 billion in revenue 
there has never been a national strike against ups which has 
had a national teamsters contract since 1979 but scattered work 
stoppages have occurred sternad said 
the last and biggest one was in 1976 when 18000 workers in 15 
northeastern states walked out for 13 weeks 
the proposed contract would raise the wages for the average ups 
fulltime driver to 18 an hour within two years sternad said ups 
drivers now make an average of 1610 per hour he said 
parttime workers mostly package handlers and truck loaders 
currently start at 8 or 9 an hour under the proposed contract 
their wages would go up 150 an hour he said 
company contributions for health benefits and employees 
pensions currently at 8300 a year for fulltime workers would 
increase to 10500 by the end of the three years sternad said 
for parttime workers the rate would increase by 105 an hour 
the proposal also offers a onetime bonus to be paid within the 
first month of ratification of 1000 to fulltimers and 500 to 
parttimers he said 
if the workers were to strike customers could turn to the us 
postal service federal express roadway package system and other 
package delivery companies analysts said but opinions were mixed 
as to whether those services could handle upss business 
ups handles 10 million pieces a day schlesinger said 
theres no way 10 million packages a day are going to be handled 
by the competitors 
however kevin murphy an analyst with morgan stanley amp co in 
new york said other package delivery services would be able to 
pick up the slack 
the world could live without united parcel it wouldnt live 
as well but it could live without them murphy said 
tony robertson an analyst with alex brown amp sons inc of 
baltimore said in the event of a strike ups would lose some 
business to its competitors but not much 
my guess is a certain percentage of air customers and ground 
customers would never come back robertson said i think any 
sort of disruption is going to cost ups some market share 
sternad said no decision has been made about whether ups would 
hire replacement workers if the union was to strike 
