<TEXT>
chicagos mercantile exchange and board of trade 
have urged other exchanges to join them in endorsing a panels 
recommendation for expanded use of trading halts to curb market 
volatility 
the merc and the board of trade on wednesday jointly proposed 
revising their circuit breakers and procedures on stock index 
futures 
circuit breakers halt trading when certain triggers are reached 
they are usually keyed to movement in the dow jones industrial 
average 
the revised circuit breakers modify existing price limits on 
both the merc and the board of trade which since 1988 have been 
set in coordination with the new york stock exchange the nyse 
calculates its circuit breakers based on the dow jones industrial 
average 
in june an 18member new york stock exchange panel proposed 
halting trading for an hour when the dow moves up or down 100 
points from the previous days close 90 minutes when it moves 200 
points and two hours when it moves 300 points 
the longer halts are designed to give market participants more 
time to react 
the merc and the board of trade also endorsed a recommendation 
calling on other securities securities options and futures 
exchanges to adopt these coordinated circuit breakers 
the new york panel was formed after the 190point plunge by the 
dow on oct 13 1989 
the proposed revised circuit breakers need final approval of the 
commodities futures trading commission and are conditional on 
acceptance of the longer halts by the nyse and other exchanges 
in the meantime the merc and the board of trade will maintain 
their daily stock index futures price limits 
</TEXT>
