stc plc the parent company of britains biggest 
computer maker today said it was negotiating the sale of a 
majority stake in its computer arm to japans leading computer 
manufacturer fujitsu ltd 
such a stake in the subsidiary international computers ltd or 
icl would give fujitsu a major foothold in europe ahead of the 
creation of the single european market in 1992 while offering icl 
security for the future analysts said 
stc formerly known as standard telephones and cables confirmed 
the negotiations after fujitsu president tadashi sekizawa said 
earlier in tokyo that his company was considering purchasing an 
interest in icl but that nothing has been decided yet 
newspaper reports in britain and japan have said fujitsu would 
acquire 50 percent to 60 percent of icls equity for about 650 
million pounds or about 12 billion 
icl is worth about 12 billion pounds or 22 billion analysts 
estimate 
there have been rumors for a year about a possible equity tie 
between icl and fujitsu which already have technology links 
london analysts said 
but analysts said they were surprised that stc might sell a 
controlling stake to the japanese company such a deal could 
inflame nationalist sentiment which frequently meets foreign bids 
in britain 
this is a significant event said andrew harrington an 
analyst at the london investment firm barclays de zoete wedd ltd 
icl is the most profitable computer company of its kind in 
europe analysts said it makes mainframe computers mostly for the 
british market 
fujitsus major activity in europe is selling semiconductor 
computer chips although it makes office computers in spain and 
semiconductors in ireland it has marketing and development arms in 
britain west germany and the netherlands 
