inaugurated last july at this historic time begins the 
reconstruction 
as he said little about it in his campaign few argentines 
suspected menem had in mind selling companies taken over by his 
partys founder juan domingo peron beginning in the 1940s 
but menem concluded the entities that once were an economic 
engine had become an anchor which he is trying to cut loose 
oil production stagnated in the 1980s because the state company 
ypf lacked money and technology promising areas were never 
explored potentially an exporter argentina barely produces enough 
for domestic needs 
onethird of the state highway system of 14670 miles is in 
marginal shape or worse government assessments show private 
studies say half the roads need basic repairs 
forty percent of the locomotives are out of service at any given 
time the state train company ferrocarriles argentinos admits 
nearly half the track is so worn that train engineers creep over it 
slowly to avoid derailment 
argentines wait years to get a new telephone line only to find 
its impossible to call another city because of jammed circuits 
within buenos aires calls frequently are misdirected callers 
often cannot hear each other and sometimes they dont get a dial 
tone the system is in collapse said entel director maria 
julia alsogaray 
by all accounts staterun companies are poorly managed 
overstaffed and strangled in bureaucracy and petty corruption 
strikers often shut them down 
fares go uncollected on state trains employees of the state 
water and electricity companies get service at a discount 
politicians receive free tickets on the state airline 
the 13 biggest staterun companies which ring up huge debts 
among themselves lost nearly 4 billion in 1989 enough to pay off 
a sizable chunk of foreign debt 
buenos aires once known as one of the loveliest and most 
sophisticated capitals is getting a reputation for third world 
deprivation the city of 10 million rationed energy last year when 
drought shriveled production at alreadyoverburdened hydroelectric 
complexes 
among other problems labor unions are intransigent courts are 
too overworked to adequately enforce contracts and markets are so 
volatile that currency and interest rates seesaw daily 
so who would want to buy argentinas companies surprisingly 
bidders abound 
bell atlantic corp of the united states and telefonica of spain 
bought a controlling stake of entel by offering 214 million cash 
and 5 billion in debt securities they hope new investment and 
tighter accounting will pay off the government will sell the 
balance of the company later this year 
about 50 argentine and foreign companies agreed to improve 
nearly 6200 miles of federal highways in return for the right to 
charge tolls 
the state carrier aerolineas argentinas fetched 260 million 
cash and 2 billion in assumed debt both higher than the 
government expected when it was put to bid iberia spains state 
airline is expected to take formal ownership later this year 
for menem privatizations are a political gamble organized 
labor helped elect him and now opposes his selleverything policy 
even allies in the peronist party arent too happy 
businesses executives clamor for the state subsidies menem 
curtailed and resent the tariff reductions and freemarket 
currency exchange rate that push them to compete more aggressively 
with overseas producers provincial governors want federal revenue 
sharing increased 
menem however views economic austerity and free market 
orientation as the only way argentina might regain the prosperity 
it had through the 1940s based on the export of beef and grain in 
his view the last thing argentina needs are dinosaurlike 
moneylosers 
by selling entel for example the government will save hundreds 
of millions of dollars in interest payments on the companys debt 
it also wont have to absorb entels staggering losses which 
totaled 250 million last year 
moreover terms of the sale call for the investment of several 
hundred million dollars within two years that the government could 
hardly have afforded jobs will be saved and services improved 
menem contends 
in the energy sector 4 billion in private funds will be 
invested in oil natural gas and petrochemical projects in the next 
four years energy undersecretary julio araoz has projected 
</TEXT>
