a financially strapped commodity brokerage headed 
by chicago board of trade chairman karsten mahlmann said today it 
has tentatively accepted an investors offer to buy a substantial 
stake in the company 
the brokerage stotler and co also confirmed that it had 
brought itself into compliance with the federal governments 
minimum capital requirements 
the developments mean stotler could avert a cashflow crisis and 
will avoid restrictions on its brokerage operations while sparing 
mahlmann further embarrassment 
stotlers parent company chicagobased stotler group inc made 
the announcements in a onepage statement stotler and co an 
oldline graintrading firm is stotler groups principal 
subsidiary 
stotler group did not identify the prospective investor or the 
size of the stake the party would buy in the parent company 
the statement said the offer was subject to approval by the 
investors board of directors the offer would terminate if such 
approval is not granted by 11 am edt monday stotler group said 
stotler group confirmed wednesdays board of trade announcement 
that it had brought itself into compliance with the minimum capital 
requirements of the commodity futures trading commission 
in a threeparagraph statement released late wednesday the 
board of trade said stotler had given the exchange a plan last week 
for meeting a cftc requirement that futures brokerages maintain in 
a separate account liquid assets equal to 4 percent of customer 
funds 
the exchange believes the firm has achieved the requisite 
capital requirements the exchange said 
they have at all times during this period had more than enough 
in segregated liquid assets to cover all customer segregated fund 
obligations and the exchange is continuing to monitor the 
compliance status of stotler and all other member firms the 
statement concluded 
board of trade spokesman michael oconnell said he could not 
elaborate on the statement 
officials at stotler and its parent company stotler group inc 
did not return telephone calls 
the exchange ordered stotler on monday to boost its capital to 
the required level by the close of business wednesday or face 
restrictions on its trading activities 
the parent company said stotler would try to meet the capital 
requirement by both reducing the size of its business and seeking 
outside financial help without which it said stotler might have 
trouble meeting its debt obligations 
the exchange can force a brokerage out of the business of 
trading for customers if the capital level falls below 4 percent of 
customer funds 
stotler groups stock which trades on the american stock 
exchange closed unchanged at 562 wednesday 
stotlers capital problems are seen as a major embarrassment to 
mahlmann now in his fourth consecutive oneyear term as chairman 
of the worlds largest commodity futures exchange 
mahlmann has said he has not been involved in stotlers 
daytoday operations for several years 
people in the commodities business said wednesday that some of 
stotlers customers were liquidating their accounts wednesday and 
others were transferring to other brokerages but they couldnt 
provide specifics 
we dont see any of that on the floor because its all done in 
the back offices but it is going on said john frazier director 
of agricultural trading for gerald inc a commodity brokerage 
stotler one of the countrys 10 largest commodity brokerages 
is an oldline firm with its roots in the grain business the 
company also trades financial futures which have outstripped 
agricultural commodities in trading volume in recent years 
