<TEXT>
claims by western commercial banks 
expanded by 98 percent on eastern europe last year and by 184 
percent on the soviet union according to a new survey released 
thursday 
the bank of international settlements survey said the banks 
claims including loans plus accrued interest on eastern europe 
went up by 33 billion during the julydecember period to 96 
billion following a 53 billion increase in the first half 
claims on the soviet union stood at 432 billion at the end of 
the year rising by 19 billion in the second half after 
increasing by 48 billion in the first half undisbursed credit 
commitments also continued to expand 
at the same time the soviet union drew down its deposits with 
the reporting western banks by 13 billion according to the 
survey 
the other major eastern european borrowers during the second 
half of 1989 were east germany at 800 million and czechoslovakia 
at 700 million claims on east germany totaled 17 billion and on 
czechoslovakia were 54 billion at the end of the year claims on 
hungary totaled 119 billion up 100 million and were 10 
billion on poland down 200 million 
lending to third world countries excluding opec members 
dropped by 92 billion to 3056 billion of these claims on 
latin american countries declined by 77 billion to 1761 
billion including a 33 billion decline in claims on brazil and a 
2 billion drop in claims on argentina 
the declines occurred in spite of the accumulation of interest 
arrears by these two countries and in the case of argentina an 
increase in claims on private nonbank entities the survey said 
the reduction in claims on brazil appears to have resulted partly 
from informal buybacks of official debt at secondary market 
discounts 
claims on mexico fell by 15 billion to 597 billion and 
claims on chile dropped 1 billion to 93 billion the survey said 
colombia borrowed 300 million after signing a new lending 
accord with creditor banks bringing total claims on that country 
to 63 billion 
claims on members of the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries went up by 19 billion to 1015 billion including a 2 
billion increase for iraq and rises of 400 million each for 
