<TEXT>
as expected atampt on thursday reported lower 
secondquarter earnings a 64 percent drop it attributed to 
declining equipment sales and unexpectedly high startup costs for 
the companys new credit card 
american telephone amp telegraph co warned of an expected drop in 
earnings in an unusual announcement three weeks ago but it did not 
say how steep it would be 
that announcement sent atampts stock price tumbling atampt is the 
nations most widely held stock 
but the market had little reaction to the actual profit decline 
which was within the expectations of industry analysts atampt shares 
rose 37 cents to close at 3750 on the new york stock exchange 
atampt said it earned 657 million or 60 cents a share in the 
quarter ended june 30 down from 699 million or 65 cents a share 
in the same quarter of 1989 
revenue fell to 903 billion from 926 billion a year earlier 
it was the phone companys first quarterly earnings drop since 
december 1988 when atampt lost 334 billion that loss the 
companys first ever resulted from a 672 billion charge it took 
against earnings to pay for a modernization program 
for the first six months of the year atampt earned 133 billion 
or 122 per share up from 129 billion or 120 a share 
revenue totaled 179 billion virtually unchanged from the same 
period of 1989 
atampt said the disappointing results last quarter were due mostly 
to slower sales of corporate telephone systems data communications 
gear and equipment sold to the federal government the company also 
blamed unexpectedly high costs for processing applications for its 
universal card which combines a mastercard or visa with telephone 
charge privileges 
the new yorkbased company blamed the 2 percent drop in 
equipment sales on a sluggish economy it said the introduction of 
the universal card in march produced twice the expected number of 
applications 
atampt also said its longdistance revenue was down 18 percent in 
the quarter due to less favorable access charge settlements with 
local phone companies and customer shifts to lowercost atampt 
services however the volume of longdistance calls rose 7 percent 
industry analysts said the fact longdistance volume rose while 
revenue declined pointed to the increasingly competitive nature of 
the long distance phone business 
atampt has been shifting its business customers to contracts that 
save them money to keep them from fleeing to competitors but it 
has come at a price in terms of what has happened to revenue 
growth said charles nichols who follows atampt for 
prudentialbache securities inc 
nichols said the secondquarter results also demonstrate how 
closely atampts fortunes are tied to the economy as economic growth 
slumps businesses spend less on phone systems and computers such 
as those sold by atampt 
in addition he said the pace of growth in longdistance volume 
has been slowing as the economy weakens 
despite the secondquarter problems atampt said it stood by its 
forecast that earnings for all of 1990 would exceed its record 1989 
earnings of 27 billion 
these results do not alter our confidence in our direction or 
our future prospects chairman robert e allen said in a news 
release 
gregory sawers an analyst at the investment firm sanford c 
bernstein amp co said it is difficult to predict earnings for atampt 
and other phone companies 
this is really virgin territory for investors in the sense 
theres never been a truly competitive long distance industry in 
this country he said 
that uncertainty was demonstrated earlier this week when united 
telecommunications inc parent of no 3 long distance company us 
sprint reported a 55 percent drop in its secondquarter earnings 
the news took industry analysts by surprise and sent the companys 
stock price sliding 
also this week no 2 mci communications corp said its 
secondquarter earnings rose 20 percent from a year earlier 
