<TEXT>
a major waste disposal company thursday 
unveiled a program to allow new york communities to choose whether 
they want landfills or recycling centers rather than letting the 
state decide for them 
were asking that communities become our partners not just in 
developing a site but in locating a site browningferris 
industries inc chairman william ruckelshaus said 
bfi based in houston said its community partnership plan was 
limited for now to new york state the company said new york was 
selected because it needs landfills and because the process of 
opening new landfills has stopped 
only three new landfills have opened in new york since 1986 
while hundreds have closed and hundreds more are under order to 
close bfi spokesman gary brotherton said no landfill sites are 
selected in advance under bfis plan 
we believe it is up to the community to decide whether or not 
they want such a facility ruckelshaus said if they decide 
theyd like to go forward with a site wed like to participate 
ruckelshaus who twice headed the federal environmental 
protection agency and was an acting director of the fbi said if 
communities decide they dont want a landfill in their area bfi 
wont request permission from the statees solid waste management plan 
to expand 
landfill capacity to complement recycling and incineration 
facilities 
