<DOCNO> AP900719-0269 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a double hull creates a ship within a ship it 
is two layers of steel separated by a gap of air around the sides 
and bottom of an oil tanker as an extra layer of protection 
environmental groups in a letter to a congressional committee 
this month said requiring doublehull tankers was the single 
most important step congress can take to prevent oil spills 
a compromise is pending in congress to have two hulls on new 
tankers and to retrofit or phase out singlehulled tankers within 
20 years the house originally wanted a 15year timetable while the 
senate asked for more study 
a double hull is not a beall or endall but weve got to 
build redundancy into the system said clifton curtis president 
of the oceanic society 
curtis called the compromise a signficant victory but he 
added we are sorely displeased with the fact that the retrofit 
schedule is not more rapid 
advocates of double hulls say they would limit the impact of oil 
spills if a tanker runs aground because a reef or manmade object 
would have to gash both layers to spill oil 
a coast guard study of 30 tanker groundings between 1969 and 
1973 said 96 percent of the spills would have been averted if the 
vessels had double hulls 
a double hull would not have prevented the exxon valdez spill 
but some studies say less crude oil would have fouled prince 
william sound in the nations worst oil spill 
double hulls are an extra margin of safety to prevent or 
minimize marine accidents said us coast guard commandant j 
william kime 
but critics say double hulls also may have drawbacks water can 
rush in between layers of the steel and make a ship settle lower 
thereby leaking more oil there are also fears explosive vapors 
could gather between the gaps 
double hulls are also more expensive it would have cost 10 
percent to 15 percent more to build a double hull on the 125 
million exxon valdez its damaged hull was repaired with 3000 tons 
of new steel but it still doesnt have a double hull 
retrofitting the 153 us tankers at 30 million each would cost 
46 billion the same work on 900 foreignflagged tankers could be 
as high as 10 billion industry officials said 
but the oil industry believes the debate is misdirected 
if an airplane crashes into a mountain we dont build planes 
that can withstand the impact we try to find out why and prevent 
it from happening again said sean connaughton of the american 
petroleum institute 
if we have ships running into underwater mountains we end up 
with people calling for ships that can withstand that type of 
collision connaughton said 
meanwhile some companies arent waiting for congress 
houstonbased conoco inc ordered two doublehull tankers in 
april and said it would order doublehull ships in the future 
norways statoil the largest producer of north sea crude oil 
said in june that it was ordering five new tankers two with double 
hulls and three with double or partial double bottoms 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

